\name{lavaan.survey.ordinal}
\alias{lavaan.survey.ordinal}
\title{Complex survey analysis of ordinal structural equation models}
\description{
  Fits an ordinal \pkg{lavaan} model while incorporating a complex sampling
  design. Thresholds and polychoric correlations are estimated with sampling
  weights, and their design-based covariance matrix is estimated from replicate
  weights generated by the \pkg{survey} package.
}
\usage{
lavaan.survey.ordinal(lavaan.fit, survey.design, ordered = NULL,
                      estimator = c("WLSMV", "DWLS"),
                      rep.type = "auto", replicates = NULL,
                      point.wls = c("auto", "lavaan", "design"),
                      mi.pooling = c("auto", "parameters", "sample.statistics"),
                      within.variance = c("auto", "replicate",
                                          "lavaan.robust", "naive"))
}
\arguments{
  \item{lavaan.fit}{
    A \code{\linkS4class{lavaan}} object for an ordinal model,
    typically fitted with \code{ordered=} and \code{estimator="WLSMV"}.
  }
  \item{survey.design}{
    A \code{\link{svydesign}}, \code{\link{svrepdesign}}, or
    \code{svyimputationList} object. Traditional survey designs are converted
    internally with \code{\link{as.svrepdesign}}.
  }
  \item{ordered}{
    Character vector of ordered variables. If omitted, the ordered observed
    variables are taken from \code{lavaan.fit}.
  }
  \item{estimator}{
    Ordinal WLS estimator passed to \pkg{lavaan}. The default is \code{"WLSMV"}.
  }
  \item{rep.type}{
    Replicate-weight type passed to \code{\link{as.svrepdesign}} when
    \code{survey.design} is not already a replicate design. The default
    \code{"auto"} uses \code{"JKn"} for stratified designs and \code{"JK1"} for
    unstratified designs.
  }
  \item{replicates}{
    Optional number of bootstrap replicates, passed through to
    \code{\link{as.svrepdesign}} for bootstrap-type replicate designs.
  }
  \item{point.wls}{
    Controls the WLS weight matrix used for point estimation. The default
    \code{"auto"} uses the inverse diagonal of the design-based Gamma matrix
    for all-ordinal models and lavaan's usual WLS weight matrix for mixed
    ordinal/continuous models. Explicit \code{"design"} and \code{"lavaan"}
    values are available for sensitivity checks.
  }
  \item{mi.pooling}{
    Multiple-imputation pooling strategy for \code{svyimputationList} designs.
    The default \code{"auto"} uses pooled sample statistics for all-ordinal MI
    models and Rubin parameter pooling for mixed ordinal/continuous MI models.
    \code{"sample.statistics"} pools thresholds, means, covariance/correlation
    statistics, and their design-based covariance matrix before refitting one
    model. \code{"parameters"} fits each imputed dataset separately and pools
    free parameters and their covariance matrix using Rubin's rules. With
    \code{point.wls = "lavaan"}, this parameter-pooling path analyzes each
    imputation with lavaan sampling weights, which is closer to Mplus
    \code{TYPE = IMPUTATION}.
  }
  \item{within.variance}{
    Within-imputation variance estimator used when
    \code{mi.pooling = "parameters"}. The default \code{"auto"} uses
    \code{"replicate"} when replicate-weight designs are available. The
    \code{"replicate"} option refits the lavaan model for each set of replicate
    weights within each imputed dataset and estimates the within-imputation
    covariance matrix with \code{\link{svrVar}}. The \code{"naive"} option uses
    the usual lavaan covariance matrix from the sampling-weighted fit in each
    imputation; this is faster and useful for Mplus-nearer diagnostics, but it
    does not incorporate clusters or strata in the within-imputation covariance
    matrix. The \code{"lavaan.robust"} option is reserved for a lavaan
    cluster-robust fast path, but current lavaan versions do not support
    clustered estimation together with ordered/categorical indicators, so this
    option currently stops with an informative error.
  }
}
\details{
  This function is an initial ordinal implementation. It supports single-group
  and multiple-group models where all observed model variables are ordered. If
  \code{survey.design} is a \code{svyimputationList}, thresholds, polychoric
  correlations, and their design-based covariance matrix are pooled across
  imputations. This also applies to multiple-group ordinal models, including
  loading and threshold invariance constraints. Mixed continuous/ordinal
  observed-variable sets have an experimental single-group and multiple-group
  proof-of-concept path, including multiple imputation. For these mixed models,
  the defaults use a Mplus-nearer parameter-pooling path for mixed MI models,
  with replicate-based within-imputation covariance estimation when replicate
  weights are available. The faster \code{within.variance = "naive"} option is
  available for diagnostics and Mplus-nearer comparisons. The
  \code{point.wls = "design"} and \code{mi.pooling = "sample.statistics"}
  options keep the original design-based pooled-statistic implementation
  available for sensitivity checks. The selected mode, MI pooling strategy,
  point WLS strategy, and within-imputation variance strategy are printed when
  relevant and stored as \code{attr(fit, "lavaan.survey.info")}.
}
\value{
  An object of class \code{\linkS4class{lavaan}} for
  \code{mi.pooling = "sample.statistics"} or non-MI designs. For
  \code{mi.pooling = "parameters"} and for mixed MI models under the
  \code{"auto"} default, a \code{lavaan.survey.mi} object with \code{coef},
  \code{vcov}, \code{print}, and \code{summary} methods is returned.
}
\seealso{
  \code{\link{lavaan.survey}},
  \code{\link{as.svrepdesign}},
  \code{\link{lavaan}}
}
\keyword{survey}
\keyword{models}
